Catalan Numbers

Relevant For...

  • Number Theory >
    Integer Sequences

The Catalan numbers are a sequence of positive integers that appear in many counting problems in combinatorics. They count certain types of lattice paths, permutations, binary trees, and many other combinatorial objects. They satisfy a fundamental recurrence relation, and have a closed-form formula in terms of binomial coefficients.

The Catalan numbers C0,C1,…,Cn,…C_0,C_1, \ldots, C_n,\ldotsC0​,C1​,…,Cn​,… are given by the formula

Cn=1n+1(2nn). C_n = \frac{1}{n+1}\dbinom{2n}{n}. Cn​=n+11​(n2n​).

The first few Catalan numbers are

C0=1C1=1C2=2C3=5C4=14C5=42.\begin{aligned} C_0 &= 1\\ C_1 &= 1\\ C_2 &= 2\\ C_3 &= 5\\ C_4 &= 14\\ C_5 &= 42. \end{aligned}C0​C1​C2​C3​C4​C5​​=1=1=2=5=14=42.​

It is not immediately clear from the definition that the Cn C_n Cn​ are integers, but this will follow from many of the theorems proved below.

Dyck Paths and Acceptable Sequences

The number of valid parenthesis expressions that consist of nnn right parentheses and nnn left parentheses is equal to the nthn^\text{th}nth Catalan number. For example, C3=5C_3 = 5C3​=5 and there are 5 ways to create valid expressions with 3 sets of parenthesis:

Considering right parenthesis to be +1s, and left -1s, we can write this more formally as follows:

The number of sequences a1,a2,…,a2na_1,a_2, \ldots, a_{2n}a1​,a2​,…,a2n​ of 2n2n2n terms that can be formed by using nnn copies of +1+1+1's and nnn copies −1-1−1's whose partial sums satisfy

a1+a2+⋯+ak≥0a_1+a_2+\cdots+a_k \ge 0a1​+a2​+⋯+ak​≥0

for k=1,2,3,…,2nk=1,2,3, \ldots, 2nk=1,2,3,…,2n equals the nthn^\text{th}nth Catalan number.

Let us call a sequence of nnn copies of +1+1+1's and nnn copies of −1-1−1's to be acceptable if it satisfies the above condition, and unacceptable otherwise. We denote the number of acceptable sequences by AnA_nAn​ and the number of unacceptable sequences by UnU_nUn​.

The total number of sequences of +1+1+1's and −1-1−1's can be regarded as a permutation of objects with two different types with nnn different objects of one type and nnn of the other. So the total number of such sequences is

(2nn)=2n!n!n!.\dbinom{2n}{n} = \frac {2n!}{n!n!}.(n2n​)=n!n!2n!​.

So An=(2nn)−Un, A_n =\dbinom{2n}{n} - U_n,An​=(n2n​)−Un​, and the next step is to count Un U_nUn​.

Consider an unacceptable sequence of nnn copies of +1+1+1's and nnn copies of −1-1−1's. Then there is a smallest kkk for which the partial sum a1+a2+⋯+aka_1+a_2+\cdots+a_ka1​+a2​+⋯+ak​ is negative. By minimality of k, k,k, there must be an equal number of +1+1+1's and −1-1−1's preceding ak.a_k.ak​. So we must have k k k odd, a1+a2+⋯+ak−1=0,a_1+a_2+\cdots+a_{k-1} = 0,a1​+a2​+⋯+ak−1​=0, and ak=−1a_k = -1ak​=−1. So among the terms (a1,a2,...,ak)(a_1,a_2,...,a_k)(a1​,a2​,...,ak​) there are k−12\frac{k-1}{2}2k−1​ copies of +1+1+1's and k−12+1=k+12\frac{k-1}{2}+1=\frac{k+1}{2} 2k−1​+1=2k+1​ copies of −1-1−1's. Among the remaining terms ak+1,....,a2n,a_{k+1},....,a_{2n},ak+1​,....,a2n​, there are (n−k−12)\big(n - \frac{k-1}{2}\big)(n−2k−1​) copies of +1+1+1's and (n−k+12)\big(n - \frac{k+1}{2}\big)(n−2k+1​) copies of −1-1−1's.

Now consider the effect of reversing the sign of each of the first kkk terms, that is, replacing aia_iai​ with −ai-a_i−ai​ for i=1,2,…,ki= 1,2, \ldots, ki=1,2,…,k and leaving the rest unchanged. Now this new sequence obtained, say b1,b2,b3,…,b2n,b_1,b_2,b_3, \ldots, b_{2n},b1​,b2​,b3​,…,b2n​, will have n+1n+1n+1 copies of +1 +1 +1's and n−1n-1n−1 copies of −1 -1 −1's (since they add up to 2).

This gives a function f f f from the set of unacceptable sequences to the set of sequences of ±1 \pm 1 ±1 terms that add up to 2 2 2. To see that f ff is a bijection, construct its inverse: let B=b1,b2,…,b2n B = b_1, b_2,\ldots, b_{2n} B=b1​,b2​,…,b2n​ be a sequence of ±1 \pm 1 ±1 terms that add up to 2 2 2. Let k k k be the first index for which there are more +1 +1+1's in b1,…,bk b_1,\ldots,b_k b1​,…,bk​ than −1 -1−1's. (There must be such a k k k since the sum of all the terms is positive.) Then define g(B) g(B) g(B) to be the (unacceptable) sequence −b1,−b2,…,−bk,bk+1,bk+2,…,b2n -b_1, -b_2, \ldots, -b_k, b_{k+1}, b_{k+2}, \ldots, b_{2n} −b1​,−b2​,…,−bk​,bk+1​,bk+2​,…,b2n​. It is clear that f f f and g g g are inverses.

Now the number of sequences of n+1n+1n+1 copies of +1+1+1's and n−1n-1n−1 copies of −1-1−1's is 2n!(n+1)!(n−1)!\frac{2n!}{(n+1)!(n-1)!}(n+1)!(n−1)!2n!​. By the bijection, this is also equal to the number of unacceptable sequences. So the total number of unacceptable sequences is

Un=2n!(n+1)!(n−1)!.U_n = \frac{2n!}{(n+1)!(n-1)!}.Un​=(n+1)!(n−1)!2n!​.

So the number of acceptable sequences is

An=(2n)!n!n!−Un=(2n)!n!n!−(2n)!(n+1)!(n−1)!=(2n)!n!(n−1)!(1n−1n+1)=(2n)!n!(n−1)!1n(n+1)=1n+1(2n)!n!n!=Cn.\begin{aligned} A_n &= \frac{(2n)!}{n!n!} - U_n\\ &= \frac{(2n)!}{n!n!} - \frac{(2n)!}{(n+1)!(n-1)!}\\ &= \frac{(2n)!}{n!(n-1)!} \left( \frac1{n}- \frac1{n+1}\right) \\ &= \frac{(2n)!}{n!(n-1)!} \frac1{n(n+1)} \\ &= \frac1{n+1} \frac{(2n)!}{n!n!} \\\\ &= C_n. \end{aligned}An​​=n!n!(2n)!​−Un​=n!n!(2n)!​−(n+1)!(n−1)!(2n)!​=n!(n−1)!(2n)!​(n1​−n+11​)=n!(n−1)!(2n)!​n(n+1)1​=n+11​n!n!(2n)!​=Cn​.​

This completes the proof. □_\square□​

Notes:

(1) These sequences also describe Dyck paths of length 2n 2n2n, which are sequences of equally-spaced northeast and southeast walks starting at the origin, ending on the xxx-axis, and never going below the xxx-axis. The bijection between acceptable sequences and Dyck paths assigns a +1+1+1 to a northeast walk and a −1 -1−1 to a southeast walk, and the acceptability condition is equivalent to the path never dropping below the starting and finishing line.

The five Dyck paths for n=3.n=3.n=3.

(2) This shows that the Catalan numbers are integers, although this also follows from the identity Cn=(2nn)−(2nn+1) C_n = \binom{2n}{n} - \binom{2n}{n+1} Cn​=(n2n​)−(n+12n​) which comes up in the above proof.

Recurrence Relation; Generating Function

A useful tool in proofs involving the Catalan numbers is the recurrence relation that describes them.

The Catalan numbers satisfy the recurrence relation

Cn+1=C0Cn+C1Cn−1+⋯+CnC0=∑k=0nCkCn−k. C_{n+1} = C_0 C_n + C_1 C_{n-1} + \cdots + C_n C_0 = \sum_{k=0}^n C_k C_{n-k}. Cn+1​=C0​Cn​+C1​Cn−1​+⋯+Cn​C0​=k=0∑n​Ck​Cn−k​.

There are several ways to prove this, but perhaps the most elegant is by appealing to Dyck paths of length 2(n+1) 2(n+1) 2(n+1), which we saw above that Cn+1 C_{n+1} Cn+1​ counts. Given a Dyck path of length 2(n+1), 2(n+1), 2(n+1), let 2(k+1) 2(k+1) 2(k+1) be the first nonzero xxx-coordinate where the path hits the x xx-axis, then 0≤k≤n 0 \le k \le n 0≤k≤n.

The path breaks up into two pieces, the part to the left of 2(k+1) 2(k+1) 2(k+1) and the part to its right. The part to the right is a Dyck path of length 2(n−k) 2(n-k) 2(n−k), so it is counted by Cn−k C_{n-k} Cn−k​. The part to the left is a northeast step, then a Dyck path of length 2k 2k 2k, and then a southeast step. (\big((The middle path is a Dyck path "on stilts"; it never dips below its starting point because it cannot hit the x xx-axis earlier than 2(k+1).) 2(k+1).\big) 2(k+1).) There are Ck C_k Ck​ of these. So there are a total of CkCn−k C_k C_{n-k} Ck​Cn−k​ paths which hit the x xx-axis first at 2(k+1) 2(k+1) 2(k+1), and summing these terms up gives Cn+1 C_{n+1} Cn+1​, which is the recurrence relation. □_\square □​

If n+1=3 n+1=3 n+1=3, then Cn+1 C_{n+1} Cn+1​ counts the five Dyck paths pictured above:

  • Path 1 has k=2 k = 2 k=2, counted in C2C0 C_2C_0 C2​C0​.
  • Path 2 has k=2 k = 2 k=2, counted in C2C0 C_2C_0 C2​C0​.
  • Path 3 has k=1 k = 1 k=1, counted in C1C1 C_1C_1 C1​C1​.
  • Path 4 has k=0 k = 0 k=0, counted in C0C2 C_0C_2 C0​C2​.
  • Path 5 has k=0 k = 0 k=0, counted in C0C2 C_0C_2 C0​C2​.

The middle path of length 4 4 4 in paths 1 and 2, and the top half of the left peak of path 3, are the Dyck paths on stilts referred to in the proof above.

This recurrence is useful because it can be used to prove that a sequence of numbers is the Catalan numbers. If the sequence (((call it Sn)S_n)Sn​) satisfies the same recurrence as the Catalan numbers, and has the same initial condition S0=1,S_0 = 1,S0​=1, then Sn=CnS_n=C_nSn​=Cn​ by induction.

The Catalan numbers are defined by the formula

Cn=1n+1(2nn). C_n = \frac1{n+1}\binom{2n}{n}. Cn​=n+11​(n2n​).

How many n n n are there such that 1,000≤n≤100,000 1{,}000 \le n \le 100{,}0001,000≤n≤100,000 and Cn C_n Cn​ is odd?

The generating function for the Catalan numbers is

∑n=0∞Cnxn=1−1−4x2x=21+1−4x.\sum_{n=0}^\infty C_n x^n = \frac{1-\sqrt{1-4x}}{2x} = \frac2{1+\sqrt{1-4x}}.n=0∑∞​Cn​xn=2x1−1−4x​​=1+1−4x​2​.

Let f(x)=∑n=0∞Cnxn f(x) = \sum\limits_{n=0}^\infty C_n x^n f(x)=n=0∑∞​Cn​xn. Then

xf(x)2=∑n=0∞(C0Cn+C1Cn−1+⋯+CnC0)xn+1=∑n=0∞Cn+1xn+1=f(x)−1.\begin{aligned} xf(x)^2 &= \sum_{n=0}^\infty (C_0C_n + C_1 C_{n-1} + \cdots + C_nC_0) x^{n+1} \\ &= \sum_{n=0}^\infty C_{n+1}x^{n+1} \\ &= f(x)-1. \end{aligned}xf(x)2​=n=0∑∞​(C0​Cn​+C1​Cn−1​+⋯+Cn​C0​)xn+1=n=0∑∞​Cn+1​xn+1=f(x)−1.​

So by the quadratic formula, f(x)=1±1−4x2x f(x) = \frac{1\pm \sqrt{1-4x}}{2x} f(x)=2x1±1−4x​​, but the minus sign is the only choice that makes sense, because the plus sign leads to an expression that blows up at x=0 x = 0 x=0. (\Big((Choosing the minus sign leads to an expression that has a limit as x→0x\to 0x→0 by L'Hopital's rule: lim⁡x→01−1−4x2x=lim⁡x→02(1−4x)−1/22=1.) □\lim_{x\to 0} \frac{1-\sqrt{1-4x}}{2x} = \lim_{x \to 0} \frac{2(1-4x)^{-1/2}}2 = 1.\Big)\ _\squarelimx→0​2x1−1−4x​​=limx→0​22(1−4x)−1/2​=1.) □​

Other Appearances of the Catalan Numbers

Restricted random walks:

A man walks nnn blocks north and nnn blocks west of his residence. Every day he has 2n2n2n blocks to walk. How many routes are possible if he never crosses the diagonal line from home to office?

Clearly, each acceptable route is either above the diagonal or below the diagonal and both of these paths are symmetric. So we calculate the number of paths below the diagonal and multiply it by 2. Each route is a sequence of nnn northerly blocks and nnn westerly blocks. We identify west with +1+1+1 and north with −1-1−1. Each route corresponds to a sequence a1,a2,…,a2na_1,a_2, \ldots, a_{2n}a1​,a2​,…,a2n​ of nnn copies of +1+1+1's and nnn copies of −1-1−1's. But in order for the route not to go above the diagonal, we must have

a1+a2+⋯+ak≥0a_1+a_2+\cdots+a_k \ge 0a1​+a2​+⋯+ak​≥0

for k=1,2,…,2nk=1,2, \ldots, 2nk=1,2,…,2n. So the number of acceptable routes above the diagonal equals the nthn^\text{th}nth Catalan number, and the total number of acceptable routes is

2Cn=2(n+1)×(2n)!n!n!.2C_n = \frac{2}{(n+1)} \times \frac{(2n)!}{n!n!}.2Cn​=(n+1)2​×n!n!(2n)!​.

The above diagram shows the routes below the diagonal for n=5n=5n=5. Notice that the number of such routes is equal to C5=42C_5 = 42C5​=42. So the answer is 2×42=84. □2\times 42=84.\ _\square2×42=84. □​

Binary trees:

A rooted binary tree is a tree with one root node, where each node has either zero or two branches descending from it. A node is internal if it has two nodes coming from it. How many rooted binary trees are there with nnn internal nodes? Rooted binary trees with 0,1,2,30,1,2,30,1,2,3 internal nodes.[1]

This is a good illustration of proving that a sequence equals the Catalan numbers by using the recurrence relation. Let RnR_nRn​ be the number of rooted binary trees with nnn internal nodes. Then R0=R1=1R_0=R_1 = 1R0​=R1​=1 as in the picture. Now for n≥0,n \ge 0,n≥0, suppose there is a rooted binary tree with n+1n+1n+1 internal nodes. The root node is internal. There are kkk internal nodes on the left and n−kn-kn−k internal nodes on the right, for some k.k.k. Looking at the left and right sides gives two rooted binary trees with kkk and n−kn-kn−k internal nodes, respectively. So

Rn+1=∑k=0nRkRn−k,R_{n+1} = \sum_{k=0}^n R_kR_{n-k},Rn+1​=k=0∑n​Rk​Rn−k​,

which is the same recurrence relation as the Catalan numbers. So Rn=CnR_n = C_nRn​=Cn​ for all n.n.n. □_\square□​

Polygon triangulations:

How many ways are there to cut an (n+2) (n+2)(n+2)-gon into n n n triangles, by drawing n−1 n-1 n−1 non-crossing lines between vertices of the polygon?

All the triangulations for n=4 n = 4 n=4[2]

Let Tn T_n Tn​ be the number of such triangulations, and define T0=1 T_0 = 1 T0​=1. Consider Tn+1 T_{n+1} Tn+1​, which counts triangulations of an (n+3) (n+3)(n+3)-gon. The idea is to pick an edge of that (n+3) (n+3)(n+3)-gon and classify triangulations by which triangle that edge ends up in.

Number the vertices v1,v2,…,vn+3 v_1, v_2, \ldots, v_{n+3} v1​,v2​,…,vn+3​. Suppose our edge is v1v2 v_1v_2 v1​v2​. If the triangle this edge ends up in is v1v2vk v_1v_2v_k v1​v2​vk​, then this triangle splits the polygon into two remaining polygons that must be triangulated.

  • If k=3 k = 3 k=3, then what is left is an (n+2) (n+2)(n+2)-gon. The number of triangulations like this is T0Tn T_0 T_n T0​Tn​.
  • If k=4 k=4 k=4, there is a triangle v2v3v4 v_2v_3v_4 v2​v3​v4​ on one side and an (n+1) (n+1)(n+1)-gon on the other side. The number of triangulations like this is T1Tn−1 T_1 T_{n-1} T1​Tn−1​.
  • If k=5 k = 5 k=5, there is a quadrilateral v2v3v4v5 v_2v_3v_4v_5 v2​v3​v4​v5​ on one side and an nnn-gon on the other side. The number of triangulations like this is T2Tn−2 T_2 T_{n-2} T2​Tn−2​.

Proceeding in this way,

Tn+1=T0Tn+T1Tn−1+⋯+TnT0.T_{n+1} = T_0T_n + T_1T_{n-1} + \cdots + T_n T_0.Tn+1​=T0​Tn​+T1​Tn−1​+⋯+Tn​T0​.

Also T0=1 T_0 = 1 T0​=1. This is the same recurrence relation and initial condition that the Catalan numbers satisfy, so it must be the case that Tn=Cn T_n = C_n Tn​=Cn​ for all n n n. □_\square□​

For the proof of the theorem on the number of valid parenthesis expressions, it's crucial to show f and g are inverses, not only the transformation from f to g and vice versa, but also to show that for any element(any permutation of n+1 +1's and n-1 -1's) in the domain of g, its range is in the domain of f.
